(879, 'default', 'Proposal has been Created', 9, 'App\\Models\\CRM\\Proposal\\Proposal', 69, 'App\\Models\\Core\\Auth\\User', '{\"attributes\":{\"subject\":\"Decapolis 500ha hybrid maize farming proposal 2023 - 2026\",\"deal\":{\"id\":15,\"title\":\"Decapolis Multi Concept Limited 500 Hectares Hybrid Maize Farming Project 2023.\",\"value\":1000000000,\"pipeline_id\":4,\"stage_id\":22,\"contextable_type\":\"App\\\\Models\\\\CRM\\\\Organization\\\\Organization\",\"contextable_id\":36,\"lost_reason_id\":null,\"status_id\":13,\"created_by\":69,\"owner_id\":69,\"description\":\"| **Decapolis 500ha Maize Farm Project Proposal**<br>**(Hybrid Maize Farming) 2023.**<br>\\u00a0 |\\n| ------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\\n| **IMPLEMENTERS**: \\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0<br>\\u00a0 | Decapolis Multi Concept Limited RC1479264.<br>\\u00a0 |\\n| **OFFICE ADDRESS**: | #8, Nigerian Air Force Shopping Mall, Kuje Area Council, Federal Capital Territory. Abuja Nigeria. forraphael@gmail.com; info@decapolis.com.ng<br>\\u00a0 |\\n| **CONTACTS**: | +234 802 417 5393, +234 902 709 9270. |\\n| **LOCATION OF FARM PROJECT:** |\\n| **CURRENT** **FARM LOCATION**: | Ika District, Enjema Ward IV, Ankpa Local Government Area, Kogi State Nigeria.<br>\\u00a0 |\\n| **LAND SIZE**: | 20 hectares.<br>\\u00a0 |\\n| **NEW FARM PROJECT LAND LOCATION**: | Abejukolo Bagana Road Omala LGA Kogi State Nigeria.<br>\\u00a0 |\\n| **Project Duration** | 36 Months. April 2023 \\u2013 April 2026\\u00a0 |\\n| **LAND SIZE**: | 500 hectares. |\\n| **FUND REQUEST**\\u00a0 | $1,000,000 (USD). |\\n| **EQUIPMENT:** \\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 | 25%. |\\n| **SEED\\/CHEMICALS\\/HARVEST:** | 50%. |\\n| **LAND PREPARATION**: | 15%. |\\n| **MANUAL LABOUR:** | 5%. |\\n| **CONTINGENCY:** | 3%. |\\n| **TAXES:** | 2%. |\\n\\n\\n**EXECUTIVE SUMMARY**\\nMaize, Zea mays L. (corn), is one of the most abundantly planted cereals in the world, and it is widely consumed by millions of Nigerians as a staple food.\\u00a0 It is also used for the production of animal feeds, ethanol, sweeteners, oil and other related products.\\nMaize is an important cereal crop in Sub-Saharan Africa, serving as an important staple food for more than one billion people in the region. More than 300 million Africans depend on maize as their main staple food crop. All parts of the crop can be used for food and non-food products. Maize accounts for 30\\u221250% of low-income household expenditures in Africa.\\nGlobal production of maize has averaged approximately 1,000 million metric tonnes over the past decades. With total production of about 11 MMT, Nigeria is arguably Africa\\u2019s second largest producer of maize after South Africa. Ethiopia occupies the thirdplace on the chart of largest producers of maize in Africa.\\u00a0 These countries accounted for about 39% of the continent\\u2019s total maize output in 2019. In Nigeria, the top ten maize producing states are Borno, Niger, Plateau, Katsina, Gombe, Bauchi, Kogi, Kaduna, Oyo and Taraba; these account for nearly two-thirds (64%) of the maize produced in the country.\\nAbout 45.5% of maize produced in Nigeria is used to manufacture animal feeds and nearly 98% of all animal feeds produced in Nigeria are used by poultry farmers. Maize accounts for 60-65% of poultry feeds constituents. Further, 6.5% of maize produced in Nigeria is used by brewing industries while 13% is used for the manufacturing of industrial flours, corn flakes and other confectionaries. The share of household consumption of maize however stands at 10-15%. Despite being the second largest maize producer in Africa, Nigeria\\u2019s export capacity for the agricultural product is terribly low when equated with peers like South Africa which account for nearly two-third of maize export in the continent.\\nThe relatively low maize export in Nigeria is primarily due to several factors including poor maize yield and existence of an official ban on export. Maize yield in Nigeria stands at less than two (2) tonnes per hectare relative to 4.9 tonnes per hectare and 4.2 tonnes per hectare in South Africa and Ethiopia respectively. This is due to continued usage of open pollinated variety (OPV) rather than improved hybrid seeds by the country\\u2019s maize farmers. As a result, production is low and can barely satisfy the huge maize demand within Nigeria itself, estimated at 12 \\u2013 15 MMT, thereby creating a maize supply gap of about 4 million metric tons\\u00a0 annually. The supply gap necessitated the declaration of the export ban on maize.\\u00a0\\u00a0 According to the USDA, maize imports into Nigeria doubled from 500,000 metric tonnes to 1 million metric tonnes between October 2019 and October 2020, with implications for Nigeria\\u2019s Naira, GDP, exchange rate, level of inflation, interest rates and job creation.\\nAlthough, data published by the USDA shows that Nigeria produced 11.6 million metric tons of maize in 2021, the highest quantity made in the last six decades.\\nThe figure, when compared to the 10 million metric tons recorded in 2020, shows a mere 16 per cent increase.\\n\\nIf you follow closely what is happening with maize farming in Nigeria, you will realize that the industry is experiencing decline and falling from historic heights due to insecurity and banditry in the top ten major producers of maize farming in Nigeria.\\nDecapolis has taken the initiative to Pioneer maize farming in a new terrain devoid of banditry, pastoralist conflict and over cultivated lands, furthermore, the location gives an opportunity to study new fauna and explore the social engineering of a new society where scholarly inducement and modern technology can make a huge difference.\\n\\n**WHY DECAPOLIS AND MAIZE**\\nThe Maize Farming Industry is indeed a very large industry and is thriving in almost all parts of the world, especially in developed countries with high tonnage per annum, such as the United States of America (347MMT), China (261MMT), Brazil (101.1MMT), Argentina (56.9MMT), Ukraine (38.9.MMT), Indonesia (30.7MMT), India (27.7MMT), Mexico (27.2MMT), Romania (17.4MMT), and Russia (14.3MMT). As a result, fewer, yet larger farms emerge across the industry.\\nNigeria food security situation depends largely on her ability to have 60% of her maize demand met, for protein-based items; eggs, broiler meat, cattle and fish to be at a stable price, maize farming should be pursued aggressively while the security challenges linger, this will be an uphill task.\\u00a0\\nOne thing is certain when it comes to commercial maize farming, Decapolis conducted her market research and feasibility studies before choosing our current farm location for the commencement of our maize project in 2021 and we have been able to establish a value chain for our produce.\\nOur long-term goal is to not only cultivate maize and sell it for consumption in farm markets and to retailers and consumers but to start a complimentary business, as well, by building a maize processing plant to\\u00a0process and package our maize, allowing us to contribute our quota to the global food security index that has been deteriorating, and thus threatening global food security, and more so to lift impoverished communities out of poverty, through provision of basic amenities.\\n**FARM LOCATIONS**\\nDecapolis Maize Farms is a farming outlet of Decapolis Multi Concept Limited. The pilot farm is located in Ika District, Enjema Ward 4, Ankpa Local Government Area of Kogi State (7\\u00b036\'25.9\\\"N 7\\u00b040\'54.4\\\"E). We have 20-hectares farming operations, we have done detailed market research and feasibility studies, and we have been able to secure a well\\u2013situated and suitable 500-hectare plot of farmland to commence our large-scale commercial maize farming project at Abejukolo-Bagana Road, Omala Local Government Area in Kogi state, Nigeria.\\nOur commercial maize farm project is a standard farm; hence it will be involved in commercial maize cultivation, maize processing and packaging. We will be involved in both organic commercial maize farming and non\\u2013organic commercial maize farming. We have put plans in place that will help us launch a standard and world\\u2013class maize processing plant within the first three years of officially running Decapolis Maize Farms project. We will process and package maize and ensure that they flood \\u00a0the market both in Nigeria and in other countries of the world.\\nWe will compete with the best in the industry, which is why we\\u00a0have secured 500 hectares of farm land and have plans to secure more, in due time, along with purchasing some farming equipment and machinery.\\u00a0 Additionally, we have hired some key employees who are currently undergoing training so as to fit into the ideal picture of the 21st\\u00a0century commercial maize farm workforce that we want to build.\\n**OUR CONTRIBUTION**\\nSince inception, Decapolis has engaged over 250 widows, 150 vulnerable children in harvesting where they are paid and fed daily, we have 50 married women permanently on our work schedule, more so, we provide full antenatal care (ANC) for over 5 women and counting, supported primary school education for 20 children, supported vigilantes in our location with logistics, communication equipment, training for youths on modern farm implement handling, sprayers, planters, chemical measurements, weather study, soil test and analysis, accounting and business classes. We hope to have a multiplier effect in no time.\\u00a0\\nWe are in the commercial maize farming business because we want to leverage on the vast opportunities available in the commercial farming industry to contribute our quota in growing the Nigerian economy, in national food production, global food security, and in raw materials production for industries. Exporting agricultural products from Nigeria to other countries out of our large-scale maize production will help to substantially reduce the domestic demand gap while generating surplus for the export market and, over and above all, to make a profit. We will also serve as a research center for schools and colleges, as this will encourage agricultural entrepreneurships in Nigerian schools.\\n**Cooperate Social Responsibilities (CSR)**\\nAs a cooperate organization, we understand the importance of cooperate social responsibilities, hence the need for us to carry out health care access initiatives in the pilot project locale, such as malaria treatment and prevention, deworming for school age children, and registering the most vulnerable women for antenatal care through partnership with the local health center in the same location.\\u00a0 Moreso, we have embarked on a project entitled \\u201c**Light up Ika**\\u201d a project in an impoverished community that lights up one (1) household at a time, using solar energy.\\u00a0 Our long-term goal is to light up an entire community within our project communities. Furthermore, in our current project location, we discovered that, we have over three hundred and thirty-eight (338) widows in just two of the nine communities there, hence the need for us to ensure that at least 40% our manual labourers are widows, thus enabling them to support themselves and their children.\\u00a0 Additionally, we offer educational scholarships for qualifying orphans. We also have a quarterly agricultural extension training classes in the same locality. \\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\nDecapolis Maize Farms, is well positioned to become one of the leading commercial maize farms in Nigeria, which is why we have been able to source for the best hands, and why we are working so diligently on purchasing more farm machinery with which to run the farm. We have put processes and strategies in place that will help us employ best practices when it comes to commercial maize farming as required by the regulating bodies in Nigeria.\\n**OUR PRODUCTS AND SERVICES**\\nDecapolis Maize Farms, is a commercial farm that is committed to cultivating both organic and non \\u2013 organic maize for both the Nigerian market and global market. We are in business to produce both food and raw materials for individuals and industries in commercial quantities. We will also ensure that we operate a standard maize processing and packaging plant as part of our complementary services.\\nWe are in this line of business to make profits, and we will ensure that we do all that is allowed by the law of Nigeria to achieve our business goals and objectives. These are the areas we will concentrate on in our commercial maize farms:\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 Cultivation of variety of maize (organic and non \\u2013 organic)\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 Standard Food Processing Plant\\nWhen the need arises, we will expand our efforts by cultivating related crops:\\n\\n* Rice\\n* Soy beans\\n* Wheat\\n* Cassava\\n\\n**Our Mission and Vision Statement**\\n\\n* Our vision is to become one of the leading commercial maize farms and maize processing and packing brands, not just in Nigeria, but also on the global stage.\\n* Decapolis Maize Farms, is a world-class commercial maize farm that is in business to cultivate organic,\\u00a0non \\u2013 organic, and processed maize for both the Nigerian market and international market, Decapolis is Farming to lift impoverished communities out of poverty.\\n\\nDecapolis will contribute her quota in growing the Nigerian economy, in national food production, in global food security, in raw materials production for industries, and in exporting agricultural produce from Nigeria to other countries\\n\\u00a0\\n**OUR BUSINESS STRUCTURE**\\nDecapolis Maize Farms, is a commercial maize farm that started small in Kogi State, but hopes to grow much larger, in order to compete favorably with leading commercial maize farms in the commercial farming industry both in Nigeria and on the global stage.\\nWe are aware of the importance of building a solid business structure that can support the vision of the kind of world-class business we want to own. For this reason,\\u00a0Decapolis is committed to only hiring the best hands.\\nAt Decapolis Maize Farms, we will ensure that we hire people that are qualified, hardworking, dedicated, customer-centric, and ready to work to help us build a prosperous business that will benefit all the stakeholders (the owners, partners, workforce, and customers).\\nIn view of the above, we have decided to hire qualified and competent hands to occupy the following positions at the moment;\\n\\n* Team lead\\n* Project Lead\\n* General Farm Manager\\n* Administrator\\/Accountant\\n* Sales\\/Logistics Manager\\n* Field Employees\\n* Front Desk Officer\\n\\n**Local contributors**\\no\\u00a0\\u00a0 Chief of Enjema Ward 4, Ika District, Kogi State\\no\\u00a0\\u00a0 Vigilante Area Commander.\\no\\u00a0\\u00a0 Youth Leader.\\no\\u00a0\\u00a0 Women leader.\\no\\u00a0\\u00a0 Primary School Headteacher.\\no\\u00a0\\u00a0 Hospital Director.\\n\\n***\\n\\nFor consistency, we need to decide to either use MMT or the spelled out million metric tons.\\u00a0 Also need to decide on either the American or British spelling for tons\\/tonnes and use consistently.\\u00a0\\nThis word choice may not be the best - \\\"flooding the market\\\" tends to have a negative economic connotation.\\nIs this phrase redundant?\\u00a0\\n**SWOT ANALYSIS**\\nDecapolis Maize Farms, does not intend to launch on a trial-and-error basis, hence the need to conduct a proper SWOT analysis. We know that if we get it right from the onset, we will have succeeded in creating the foundation that will help us build a standard maize farm that will favorably compete with leading commercial maize farms in Nigeria and other\\u00a0parts of the world.\\nWe are quite aware that there are several large, medium,\\u00a0and small-scale maize farms all over Nigeria.\\u00a0 However, during our feasibility studies, we discovered that the location of our maize farm project gave us an edge as it was relatively free from the threats of banditry and herders invasion, unlike our experience at the trial one-acre maize farm project in Abuja that was ravaged by herdsmen invasion. Further findings from the upper Northern states of Nigeria, who are key players in the maize farm industry, shows that, there has been an invasion of herdsmen and bandits, thereby reducing their contribution to the Nigerian metric tonnage output and affecting global food security index.\\nWe know that if a proper SWOT analysis is conducted for our business, we will be able to position our business to maximize our strength, leverage on the opportunities that will be available to us, mitigate our risks, and be equipped to confront our threats.\\nDecapolis Maize Farms, employed the services of an expert Business Analyst with bias in the commercial farming industry to help us conduct a thorough SWOT analysis and to help us\\u00a0create a business model that will help us achieve our business goals and objectives.\\nHere is a summary from the result of the SWOT analysis that was conducted on behalf of Decapolis Maize Farm Project.\\n**Strength**\\nOur strength as a commercial maize farm is in the fact that we have healthy relationships with many of the major players throughout the chain of industry,\\u00a0 including agricultural merchants who deal in maize in the commercial farms industry both suppliers and buyers within and outside our current farm location.\\nWe have used modern land preparation equipment, plough and harrow, seed planters, fertilizer applicators, sprayers, we have also partnered with Pioneer seeds and received technical and consultative supports on daily and weekly basis, through video calls and all our part time and full-time team have had at least 2 weeks intensive training on equipment and chemical handling.\\nFor the past two years, we have not had any incident of banditry or herders\\u2019 invasion within the proximities of our farm locations, unlike when we did the trial one-acre maize project in Abuja (Federal Capital Territory), where the entire crop was consumed by Fulani cattle just before harvest time.\\nWe are working toward buying some of the latest commercial farming machines, tools and maize processing equipment that will help us cultivate maize in commercial quantities with less stress. Apart from our relationships (network) and this equipment, we can confidently boast that we have some of the most experienced hands on our team.\\n**Weakness**\\nOur weakness could be that we are a new commercial maize farm in Nigeria.\\u00a0 The fact that we decided to upscale from 20ha to 500ha and diversify our farming activities could count against us, initially. We are aware of this and from our projection, we will overcome this weakness with time and turn it into a major advantage for the business.\\n**Opportunities**\\nThe opportunities that are available to us cannot be quantified; we know that there are billions of individuals who consume both organic and non \\u2013 organic maize in different forms both in Nigeria and other parts of the world. We will ensure that we maximize the opportunities available to commercial maize farmers. We know that the local and global demand for maize is anticipated to keep growing as renewable energy targets rise each year.\\nWe have already started to get request for maize supply from major maize users within poultry industry in the Federal Capital Territory, Abuja;\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 Dahmos Agroallied\\u00a0 (10,000 layers Farm)\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 Salbari Ranches (500 Dairy Cattle)\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 Mainland Farm (22,000 layers farm)\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 Ramispro (25,000 broilers a year farm)\\u00a0\\nThe above four concerns can comfortably consume 2500Tonnes of maize a year making our 500hectares project look like child\\u2019s play.\\n**Threat**\\nSome of the threats and challenges that we are likely going to face when we upscale our commercial maize farm from the current 20ha to 500ha or more, are a global economic downturn that can impact negatively on household spending, bad weather conditions, natural disasters (draughts, epidemics),\\u00a0unfavorable government policies\\u00a0\\u00a0and the arrival of \\u00a0more competitors.\\nThere is hardly anything one can do as regards these threats and challenges other than to be optimistic that things will continue to work for our good.\\n\\u00a0\\n**MARKET TRENDS**\\nOne of the common trends in the commercial line of maize farming is that most players in the industry are no longer concentrating only on non \\u2013 organic maize farming. Farmers now find it easier to run both organic maize cultivation and non \\u2013 organic maize cultivation. It is a fact that despite organic foods being expensive, the sale of organic food is on the increase, and it is indeed profitable.\\u00a0\\nDespite commercial maize farming being a centuries-old industry, this\\u00a0does not in any way make the industry over-saturated; commercial maize farmers are exploring innovative technology to continue to improve the cultivation, preservation, and processing of their product. The fact that there is always a ready market for maize makes the business highly profitable.\\nLastly, it is a common trend to find standard commercial maize farmers run a maize processing plant business alongside their farm. It is a means of maximizing profit in the business. Additionally, as maize is\\u00a0consumed by both humans and livestock, it is ideal to process, package, and ship it\\u00a0to other countries of the world.\\n\\n<br>\\n\\u00a0\\n**Our Target Market**\\nThe target markets of those who are the end consumers of maize in any form and who benefit from the business value chain of commercial maize farming is all-encompassing.\\nAlmost every household consumes maize in different forms; maize is sought after in the Nigerian industrial sectors, especially in livestock feeds, breweries, and industrial baking and cooking products and confectionaries. In essence, a commercial maize farmer should be able to sell his or her farm produce to as many people as possible including hotels, grocery stores, restaurants, livestock farmers, and production companies that make use of maize as raw materials.\\nWe will ensure that we position our business to attract consumers of maize not just in Nigeria, but also other parts of the world, which is why we will be exporting [\\\\[CG6\\\\]](#_msocom_6)\\u00a0some of our farm produce either in raw or processed form to other countries of the world.\\n**Our competitive advantage**\\nEntrepreneurs gravitate towards industries that are known to generate consistent income, which is why commercial farming is such a strong investment.\\u00a0 The world will always need food.\\nAs a matter of fact, entrepreneurs are encouraged by the government to embrace commercial farming. This is so, because part of the success of any nation is her ability to cultivate her own food and also export foods to other nations of the world.\\nDecapolis Maize Farms Project is fully aware that there are competitors when it comes to selling commercial farm produce, including maize, all over the globe, which is why we decided to carry out thorough research, so as to know how to take advantage of the available market in Nigeria and in other parts of the world[\\\\[CG7\\\\]](#_msocom_7)\\u00a0.\\nWe have done our homework and have been able to highlight some factors that will give us a competitive advantage in the marketplace: effective and reliable maize farming processes that can help us sell our produce at competitive prices, strong industry network connections, and excellent relationship management.\\nAnother competitive advantage that we are bringing to the industry is the fact that we have designed our business in such a way that we will operate a fully- standardized, commercial maize farm that will also include a maize processing plant. With this, we will be able to take advantage of all the available opportunities within the industry.\\nLastly, our employees will be well taken care of, and their welfare package will be among the best within our category (start\\u2013up commercial maize farms) in the industry, meaning that they will be more than willing to build the business with us, help deliver our set goals and achieve all our aims and objectives.\\n\\n<br>\\n\\u00a0\\n**SALES AND MARKETING STRATEGY**\\nDecapolis Maize Farms Project is the commercial farming business arm of Decapolis Multi Concept Limited. For the purpose of maximizing profits, we have decided to explore all the available opportunities within the industry to achieve our corporate goals and objectives.\\nWe do not intend to rely only on the sale of our farm produce to generate income for the business. Below are the sources we intend exploring to generate income for the Decapolis Maize Farm Project.\\n\\n* Cultivation of various species of maize (both organic and non \\u2013 organic)\\n* Standard Food Processing Plant\\n* Partnerships\\n* Investment opportunities for corporate organizations and individuals.\\n\\n**Sales Forecast**\\nWe conducted a thorough market survey and feasibility study, and we were able to discover that the sales generated by a commercial farm depend on the size and nature of the commercial farm.\\nWe have perfected our sales and marketing strategies, and we are quite optimistic that we will meet, or even surpass, our set sales target of generating enough income\\/profits from the first year of operation to build the business from survival to sustainability.\\nWe have been able to critically examine the agriculture industry and commercial maize farm business, we have analyzed our chances in the industry, and we have been able to come up with the following sales forecast.\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 **Year one (Y1) Pilot Farming season on 20ha (2021)-:**\\u00a0$24,662.2\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 **Year two (Y2) Farming season on 20ha (2022) -:**\\u00a0$16,208\\n\\u00b7\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0 **Projections for Year three (Y3) Farming season on a 500ha -:**\\u00a0$510,877.5\\n**It is of importance to note that,** this projection is done based on what is obtainable in the industry and with the assumption that there won\\u2019t be any major economic crises that impact negatively on household spending, bad weather conditions and natural disasters (draughts, epidemics), and unfavorable government policies. Please note that the specific numbers in the above projection might change due to fluctuating international monetary exchange rates.\\n\\n<br>\\n\\u00a0\\n**DECAPOLIS 2021 (Y1) ESTIMATE FOR CULTIVATING A HECTARE OF PIONEER HYBRID MAIZE SEEDLING**\\n*Using a market price of N381\\/USD*\\n\\n| **ACTIVITY** | **Product Type** | **UNIT** | **COST\\/UNIT** | **TOTAL($)** |\\n| -------- | ------------ | ---- | --------- | -------- |\\n| **Land Preparation** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 |\\n| Harrowing \\/ Ridging | Mechanized | 1 ha | 65.79 | 65.79 |\\n| **Total Land preparation cost** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | **65.79** |\\n| **Inputs** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 |\\n| Seeds | Pioneer Hybrid Seeds | \\u00a0(53MK) | 110.24 | 110.24 |\\n| Fertilizer 1 | N.P.K. 20:10:10 | 8 Bags | 26.25 | 209.97 |\\n| Fertilizer | Urea NPK 46:0:0 | 4 bags | 21 | 84 |\\n| Herbicides 1 (Land Preparation) | Glyphosate | 3 Litre | 3.41 | 10.24 |\\n| Herbicides 2 (Pre-emergence) | Atrazine | 3 Litre | 3.94 | 11.81 |\\n| Herbicides 3 (Pre-emergence) | Paraquat | 3 Litre | 3.15 | 9.45 |\\n| Herbicides 4 (Post-emergence) | Paraquat | 3 Litre | 3.15 | 9.45 |\\n| Insecticide | Emamectin Benzoate | 12 sachets | 2.63 | 31.51 |\\n| Empty bags (100kg) | Jabbo | 50 Bags | 0.66 | 32.81 |\\n| **Total Input cost** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | **509.48** |\\n| **Operations\\/Labour** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 |\\n| Planting + NPK | Labour | 1Ha | 26.25 | 26.25 |\\n| Fertilizer application (Urea) | Labour | 1Ha | 15.75 x 2 | 31.51 |\\n| Insecticide & Herbicide Application | Labour | 1Ha | 7.87 x 3 | 23.62 |\\n| Harvesting | Labour | 1Ha | 39.37 | 39.37 |\\n| Threshing | Labour | 2days\\/Ha | 0.78x 50 | 39.37 |\\n| **Total Operation cost** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | **160.12** |\\n| **Total Variable Cost** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | **$735.39** |\\n\\n\\u00a0\\n**DECAPOLIS 2021 (Y1) MAIZE PROJECT COST BENEFIT RATIO.**\\nSeed potential 10 to 12 tonnes\\/hectare (ha).\\nAverage yield achieved; 5 to 7 tonnes\\/ha\\nHowever, let\\u2019s take the least for the purpose of budgeting = 5T\\/ha, that is 50 bags\\/ha\\nMarket price in 2021 per 100kg bag; $39.37 - $62.99.\\nWe will use the least price for the purpose of budgeting; $39.37\\n**Therefore;**\\n50 Bags (5T) \\\\* $39.37 equals **$1,968.5**\\n\\u00a0\\n**TOTAL EXPENSES**; **$735.39**\\nIncome from sales using 5T\\/ ha at $39.37 equals $1968.5\\nTotal sales \\u2013 expenses; **$**1,968.5 \\u2013 $735.39 = $1,233.11\\/ha\\nTotal Revenue on a Hectare = **$1,233.11\\/ hectare**\\nTherefore;\\n\\u00a0\\n**TOTAL REVENUE GENERATED IN (Y1) 20HECTARES MAIZE PROJECT;**\\n**$1,233.11\\\\*20ha = $24,662.2**\\n\\n<br>\\n\\u00a0\\n**DECAPOLIS 2022 (Y2) ESTIMATE FOR CULTIVATING A HECTARE OF PIONEER HYBRID MAIZE SEEDLING**\\n*Using a market price of N447\\/USD*\\n\\n| **Activity** | **Product Type** | **Unit** | **Cost\\/Unit** | **Total (**$**)** |\\n| -------- | ------------ | ---- | --------- | --------- |\\n| **Land Preparation** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 |\\n| Ploughing \\/harrowing | Mechanized | 1ha | 156.60 | 156.60 |\\n| **Total Land preparation cost** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | $**156.60** |\\n| **Inputs** | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 | \\u00a0 |\\n| Seed